Overview – E-Commerce Sales Analysis
Objective

You’ve joined an e-commerce startup as a data analyst. Your manager wants key business insights from the sales dataset to optimize operations. Let’s dive in.



Dataset

You can download the dataset from Kaggle:

https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/carrie1/ecommerce-data


You’ll analyze:



Orders per month

Revenue trends

Top-selling products

High-value customers

Geographical insights

INSTRUCTIONS:
MySQL Setup Instructions
0) Download data from kaggle

Open kaggle link in previous article(Overview) and click on download --> 'Download dataset as zip' --> Unzip file



Execute below commands in mysql workbench



1) Create database & table



CREATE DATABASE IF NOT EXISTS ecommerce;

USE ecommerce;



DROP TABLE IF EXISTS sales_data;

CREATE TABLE sales_data (

    InvoiceNo   VARCHAR(20),

    StockCode   VARCHAR(20),

    Description VARCHAR(200),

    Quantity    INT,

    InvoiceDate VARCHAR(25),

    UnitPrice   FLOAT,

    CustomerID  VARCHAR(20),

    Country     VARCHAR(100)

);





2) Find the mysql server upload folder



SHOW VARIABLES LIKE 'secure_file_priv';



* If it shows a path (e.g., `C:/ProgramData/MySQL/MySQL Server 8.0/Uploads/`),

go to that path in file explorer & create portfolio1 folder inside Uploads folder

and copy downloaded *data.csv* into that folder





3) load csv into table :

LOAD DATA INFILE 'C:/ProgramData/MySQL/MySQL Server 8.0/Uploads/portfolio1/data.csv'

INTO TABLE sales_data

CHARACTER SET latin1

FIELDS TERMINATED BY ',' OPTIONALLY ENCLOSED BY '"'

LINES TERMINATED BY '\n'

IGNORE 1 LINES

(InvoiceNo, StockCode, @Description, Quantity, @InvoiceDate, @UnitPrice, @CustomerID, Country)

SET

  Description = NULLIF(CONVERT(TRIM(@Description) USING utf8mb4), ''),

  UnitPrice   = NULLIF(@UnitPrice, ''),

  CustomerID  = NULLIF(@CustomerID, ''),

  InvoiceDate = COALESCE(

                  STR_TO_DATE(TRIM(@InvoiceDate), '%m/%d/%Y %H:%i:%s'),

                  STR_TO_DATE(TRIM(@InvoiceDate), '%m/%d/%Y %H:%i')

                );





4) Cast the date column

ALTER TABLE sales_data MODIFY InvoiceDate DATETIME NULL;



5) Quick sanity checks

-- total rows

SELECT COUNT(*) FROM sales_data;

